Introduction¶

For this coursework, I will be following The universal workflow of machine learning from Deep Learning With Python by Franois Chollet. The workflow goes as such:

  1. Defining the problem and assembling a dataset
  2. Choosing a measure of success
  3. Deciding on an evaluation protocol
  4. Preparing your data
  5. Developing a model that does better than baseline
  6. Scaling up: developing a model that overfits
  7. Regularizing your model and tuning your hyperparameters

Problem and Dataset¶

I will be using the Parkinson's Data Set from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. According to the NIH, Parkinson's disease is a brain disorder that can lead to shaking, stiffness and difficulty with walking, balance, coordination and talking.

What I will be trying to predict is whether a patient has Parkinson's Disease (PD) or not. This makes for a binary classification - where there are only two outcomes, a patient has PD or does not have PD.

Measure of Success¶

The inputs will be a range of biomedical voice measurements from 31 people, 23 with Parkinson's disease (PD). Each column in the table is a particular voice measure, and each row corresponds one of 195 voice recording from these individuals. The output will be the "status" column which is set to 0 for healthy and 1 for PD. Since this is a binary classification, the metric I will be using to measure success will be accuracy.

Evaluation Protocol¶

I will be using K-Fold validation as my evaluation protocol.

# plot code taken and modified from Chollet, Franois. Deep Learning with Python. p. 74-75

def plot(train, val, metric):
    '''
    Plots training/validation loss/accuracy against each other.
    '''
    
    if metric == "loss":
        train_label = "Training Loss"
        val_label = "Validation Loss"
        title = "Training and Validation Loss"
        y_label = "Loss"
    if metric == "acc":
        train_label = "Training Accuracy"
        val_label = "Validation Accuracy"
        title = "Training and Validation Accuracy"
        y_label = "Accuracy"
        
    plt.clf()
    epochs = range(1, len(train) + 1)
    plt.figure(figsize = (7, 5))
    plt.plot(epochs, train, 'b', label = train_label, color = 'blue')
    plt.plot(epochs, val, 'b', label = val_label, color = 'darkorange')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Developing a Model¶

At this stage, what we are trying to do is build a model that does better than a baseline model. Since the data set that I am using is a binary classification data set, the model should have more than 50% accuracy to be said to have achieved satistical power.

To compile the model, I will be using sigmoid as the last-layer activation, binary_crossentropy as the loss function, adam as the optimization configuration and accuracy as metric.

Developing an Overfitting Model¶

To figure out how big of a model is required to get a good fit, an overfitting model will developed. The way to make an overfitting model is by adding layers, making the layers bigger and training for more epochs.

Build a new model that has bigger and more layers.

Regularizing the Model and Hyperparameter Tuning¶

K-Fold Validation¶

Since the size of X_train is only (156, 22), I will be using K-Fold validation to make the data more reliable.

The function will contain comments to explain the code more in-depth.

In [26]:
# K-Fold Validation code taken and modified from Chollet, Franois. Deep Learning with Python. p. 87-89

def k_fold_validation(X_train, y_train, epoch, build):
    '''
    Performs K-Fold Validation on training data that is limited.
    
    Inputs
    ------
    X_train : training data
    y_train : test data
    epoch   : number of epochs
    build   : model function
    
    Outputs
    -------
    acc_history      : equivalent to history.history['acc']
    val_acc_history  : equivalent to history.history['val_acc']
    loss_history     : equivalent to history.history['loss']
    val_loss_history : equivalent to history.history['val_loss']
    loss_scores      : loss evaluation of model
    acc_scores       : accuracy evaluation of model
    '''
    
    # train data for k folds
    k = 4
    # index is used to split the data into [index] size
    index = len(X_train) // k
    # lists to store each history.history['#']
    acc_histories = []
    loss_histories = []
    val_acc_histories = []
    val_loss_histories = []
    # lists to store each evaluation
    all_acc_scores = []
    all_loss_scores = []
    # loop through k
    for i in range(k):
        print('processing fold', i)
        # split X_train and y_train into partial_X_train, partial_y_train, X_val and y_val
        X_val = X_train[i * index: (i + 1) * index]
        y_val = y_train[i * index: (i + 1) * index]        
        partial_X_train = np.concatenate([X_train[:i * index], X_train[(i + 1) * index:]], axis = 0)
        partial_y_train = np.concatenate([y_train[:i * index], y_train[(i + 1) * index:]], axis = 0)
        # build the model
        model = build()
        # train model using partial_X_train, partial_y_train, X_val and y_val
        history = model.fit(
            partial_X_train, partial_y_train, validation_data = (X_val, y_val), epochs = epoch, batch_size = 1, verbose = 0
        )
        # evaluate the model against X_val and y_val
        results = model.evaluate(X_val, y_val, verbose = 0)
        # retrieve each history.history[#] value
        acc = history.history['acc']
        loss = history.history['loss']
        val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
        val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
        # store into the corresponding list
        acc_histories.append(acc)
        loss_histories.append(loss)
        val_acc_histories.append(val_acc)
        val_loss_histories.append(val_loss)
        # store evaluation values into corresponding list
        all_loss_scores.append(results[0])
        all_acc_scores.append(results[1])
    # once loop has completed
    # loop through the lists and calculate the mean for each epoch
    acc_history = [np.mean([x[i] for x in acc_histories]) for i in range(epoch)]
    loss_history = [np.mean([x[i] for x in loss_histories]) for i in range(epoch)]
    val_acc_history = [np.mean([x[i] for x in val_acc_histories]) for i in range(epoch)]
    val_loss_history = [np.mean([x[i] for x in val_loss_histories]) for i in range(epoch)]
    # calculate mean of scores
    loss_scores = np.mean(all_loss_scores)
    acc_scores = np.mean(all_acc_scores)
    # return values
    return acc_history, val_acc_history, loss_history, val_loss_history, loss_scores, acc_scores

For this attempt, we will try adding and removing layers from the overfitting model. Let's try removing a few hidden layers. Additionally, let's use the K-Fold validation to build the model.

def model_one():
    tf.random.set_seed(3)
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu', input_shape = (22,)))
    # model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation = 'relu'))
    # model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu'))
    # model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(8, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['acc'])
    return model

acc_one, val_acc_one, loss_one, val_loss_one, loss_scores_one, acc_scores_one = k_fold_validation(

)

Attempt Three — Adding Dropout¶

The current parameters are still not generating a good fit, so we will try more methods, such as adding dropout.

Commented lines of code are codes that were edited, added or removed from the model with the best parameters, model_two().

In [32]:
def model_dropout():
    tf.random.set_seed(3)
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu', input_shape = (22,)))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2)) # dropout added
    model.add(layers.Dense(8, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2)) # dropout added
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['acc'])
    return model

Attempt Four — Adding Regularization¶

Let's try adding L2 Regularization to the model this time.

Commented lines of code are codes that were edited, added or removed from the model with the best parameters, model_two().

In [33]:
def model_regularization():
    tf.random.set_seed(3)
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu', input_shape = (22,)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(8, activation = 'relu', kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l2(l = 0.1))) # L2 regularization added
    model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['acc'])
    return model

acc_seven, val_acc_seven, loss_seven, val_loss_seven, loss_scores_seven, acc_scores_seven = k_fold_validation(
    X_train, y_train, epoch = 100, build = model_regularization
)

plot(loss_seven, val_loss_seven, "loss")
plot(acc_seven, val_acc_seven, "acc")

The way we tell if a model shows a good fit is:

  1. The training loss decreases to a point of stability.
  2. The validation loss decreases to a point of stability and has a small gap with the training loss.

Looking at the training model that has L2 Regularization, the model shows a good fit.

Conclusion¶

Looking back on the last three plots, we can safely say that a well-behaved model has been achieved. The results between them are consistent, with each line reaching stability. The accuracy for each of them has also beaten the baseline model, which stands at 72%, while the average accuracy of the last three is 89%. I could have used Hold-Out validation on the dataset, however I found that it was not optimal as the model kept overfitting, hence the change to K-Fold validation. However, even with the change of evaluation protocol, only by adding L2 regularizer was the model able to achieve a good fit. Though, it is not to say that there are not other ways that I did not explore that may or may not have been able to improve the models.
